  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "METHOD A. Majorana representation and the damping matrixIntroduce Majorana operatorsw 2j-1 = c j + c † j, w 2j = i(c j -c † j)and collect them into a real 2L vector w. The Hamiltonian is represented as H = i 4 w T H M w with H M real and antisymmetric.",
    "Each linear jump operator can be written L m = p ℓ m,p w p and one defines the bath matrixM pq = m ℓ m,p ℓ * m,q,(5)which is Hermitian and positive semidefinite.",
    "Following third-quantization [3][4][5] the key non-Hermitian rapidity matrix isX = -4iH M + 2(M + M T),(6)and one also defines Y = -4i(M -M T) which enters the Lyapunov equation below.",
    "The eigenvalues of X are the rapidities {β k }: their real parts govern decay rates and the smallest nonzero Re β is the Liouvillian rapidity gap κ (we report κ as the central dynamical observable) [3,17].",
    "Steady covariance and Lyapunov equationThe steady-state Majorana covariance matrix Γ satisfies a Sylvester/Lyapunov equationXΓ + ΓX T = -4i(M -M T) ≡ Y,(7)which is solved numerically using standard linear algebra routines for each parameter point to obtain steady correlations and observables such as ⟨c † j c j ⟩ [3,4]."
  ],
